I know it’s a little late but... No! Servers have dual power supplies so you connect one power supply to UPS1 and the other power supply to UPS2 in case a UPS fails or you need to service it. And you connect each UPS to a separate circuit if you can and you can because you’re going to run a new circuit. Run 2 new circuits. And also run a separate ground wire to your panel and tie it to a grounding bus bar that grounds your rack. This is called a telecommunications grounding bus bar which is code for commercial installs. Not that your company would know that. Your office rack really needs a grounding bus bar with that many servers and that big of UPS. You could also install a isolated ground outlet with this.

Dude! The Ethernet spec' calls for Ethernet cables to have a minimum length of 1 meter (including any cables going to the back of patch panels). With shorter cables, you get things like crosstalk and noise messing with the signal. After all, at the frequencies used in Ethernet, the cable is really just a super long antenna with a transmitter on one end and a receiver on the other. To properly manage your cables, don't make shorter cables. Just coil them neatly or route them down into a tray and back again. Looks are NOT the most important thing in networking.

I'll be amazed if it hasn't been said already, but SMR is still bad for Unraid. If you have to rebuild the writes can take so long that the drive being rebuilt can randomly timeout and drop. CMR is still safe to shuck at 8TB+ from externals so do that if able. If not, might want to consider SMRs as better for either unassigned drives (no protection) or parity IF you tend to save new files serially (1 at a time) so that you aren't overloading parity writes.

Linus, In case you were unaware (which I'm sure you are and I'm just sanity checking) the Unraid parity method you mentioned you were using is called JBOD generically. Unraid is just an OS using Lime Tech's implementation of JBOD. I wanted to clarify so people could research the tech because JBOD is so cool and blew me away when I first saw it. I have been using Unraid for a couple years now as my home server ever since you initially showed it in '2 Gamers 1 CPU.' I found it was a perfect solution for my home server with how many 'systems' I need running on my network but only having the space and financial ability to only have one or two physical systems. I am still very surprised that Linus is not running a PC as a web appliance for routing all internet traffic and securing his home network.
I built a mini ITX PC that is based on the intel Atom CPU with 4 GB of ram over 11 years ago running Clark Connect and later upgrading to ClearOS and it still surpasses the current speed of my home fiber connection and only consumes 15 watts of power. During that same time period, I have watched many people have to power cycle home routers (which if designed right, should never need to be done unless upgrading firmware or making changes) and replace them completely every 4-5 years to keep up with speed changes or changes in use. Instead of dedicating more hardware, Linus could even dedicate a VM on his unraid server to running as a Virtual Web Appliance using physical NICs to handle the WAN and various LAN segments and eliminate unneeded hardware in the rack which overall will reduce power consumption in the rack.

Correct me if wrong: isn't the whole point of having 2x UPS is to (where possible and applicable) have each redundant PSU on a different UPS... that way you also cover for UPS failure, or you need to do UPS maintenance that requires it being powered off...
